3. Foundational Definitions

3.1 Blueprint

A blueprint is a structured hypothesis concerning the possible arrangement of parts. It is not proof that those parts can be made, joined, powered, cooled, serviced, shipped, insured, certified, or understood by the person asked to assemble them at 4:55 p.m. on a Friday.

3.2 Machine

A machine is a blueprint that has survived contact with tools, labour, materials, measurement, error, force, electricity, regulation, budget pressure, and repeated disappointment.

3.3 Tolerance

Tolerance is the formal acknowledgement that reality refuses to hold still.

It is the small numeric mercy by which engineering admits that no component will ever be exactly what the drawing says it is, because matter has opinions.

3.4 Idea

An idea is a pre-physical disturbance in the confidence field. It may become useful after substantial humiliation.

3.5 AI Product Concept

An AI product concept is an idea wearing a rendering as a costume.

