4. The Tolerance Principle

The tolerance exists because the drawing is not reality. It is an agreement about how much reality may legally misbehave before the part is rejected.

A dimension marked 50.00 mm is not a commandment handed down from the mountain. It is a target surrounded by a negotiated zone of disappointment.

For example:

Drawing Dimension	Actual Manufactured Range	Institutional Meaning
50.00 mm	49.95–50.05 mm	Acceptable deviation
50.00 mm	49.50 mm	The machine now has a personality
50.00 mm	52.00 mm	Procurement has become involved
50.00 mm	“About right”	Catastrophe pending

The tolerance is therefore not a minor detail. It is the border between design and fantasy.

A culture that ignores tolerances will inevitably produce products that exist perfectly in presentations and nowhere else.

