9. Institutional Recommendations

This paper recommends the immediate adoption of the following policies across all technology development environments.

9.1 Mandatory Reality Review

No product concept may be described as “built” until at least one qualified engineer has frowned at it in person.

9.2 Blueprint Warning Labels

All drawings, renderings, and AI-generated product concepts shall include the following notice:

This document does not constitute a machine.
Physical implementation may involve engineers, cost, time, failure, and adult supervision.

9.3 Tolerance Literacy Training

All founders, strategists, innovation leads, and pitch deck authors must complete a basic course in dimensional tolerance before using the phrase “we can just manufacture it.”

9.4 Prototype Humility Period

After the first prototype is assembled, all executive enthusiasm shall be suspended for 72 hours while technicians explain what happened.

9.5 Ban on the Phrase “It’s Just”

The phrase “it’s just” shall be prohibited in all design meetings.

Examples include:

* “It’s just a hinge.”
* “It’s just a sensor.”
* “It’s just a housing.”
* “It’s just wiring.”
* “It’s just software talking to hardware.”

Nothing is just anything.

